1muF90RAY0eCxgaIAY1N4wAAUAY0NjQEGrsprCMrp85jyMejl38SKx4DGhsghqeX r2OalJ52UkRjAwBUAY0NDYHGbgrrnMazs7PyaWDPsxh4cQAiiWlSzr68rJ3MZKCx AQCqgMaGhkAqtIN1LLYwe7hlDkQ/72fGSY0VccCLAzDF7HGAYg+f/1E7mclAYwMA style="top:64.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt"><span style="color: var(--bs-body-color); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);">eviated as DENS) [20].</span></p><div id="page0" style="width:576.0pt;height:782.9pt"><div id="page0" style="width:576.0pt;height:782.9pt"> <p style="top:312.9pt;left:298.1pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>A. EMOTIONAL EVENT</i></p> <p style="top:325.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">Emotion is a complex phenomenon which is embedded</p> <p style="top:337.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">within a context [21]. Moreover, emotion is transient in nature</p> <p style="top:349.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">and is not available throughout the stimulus duration. In fact,</p> <p style="top:361.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">more than one aspect could be embedded within the stimulus</p> <p style="top:373.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">context, and different participants can feel emotion at differ-</p> <p style="top:385.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">ent points of time considering various aspects. However, most</p> <p style="top:397.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">of the datasets recorded to date [2], [3] ignore the transient</p> <p style="top:408.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">nature of emotions and provide a single emotional category</p> <p style="top:420.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">for the whole stimulus duration. Although the stimulus has</p> <p style="top:432.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">emotional information, it has some non-emotional aspects</p> <p style="top:444.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">too, which could lead to mind-wandering activity. Although</p> <p style="top:456.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">there are some attempts to get continuous subjective feedback</p> <p style="top:468.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">on emotional experience and neural activity, the experimental</p> <p style="top:480.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">method involved multiple watching of the stimulus and</p> <p style="top:492.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">retrospective collection of emotional experience [22], [23],</p> <p style="top:504.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">[24], [25], [26]. The retrospective collection depends on</p> <p style="top:516.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">autobiographical memory and can raise biases across subjects</p> <p style="top:529.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">depending on their capability to recall [27]. Also, repetitive</p> <p style="top:541.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">viewing effects can bias the ratings and underlying neural</p> <p style="top:552.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">effects [27]. Hence, an experimental paradigm is needed to</p> <p style="top:564.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">record the participants’ feedback dynamically, with minimal</p> <p style="top:576.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">distraction during emotion processing and minimizing the</p> <p style="top:588.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">memory recall biases. In this work, we are introducing</p> <p style="top:600.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">a novel paradigm in which the time-stamp of emotional</p> <p style="top:612.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">feelings can be marked online that can be further utilized</p> <p style="top:624.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">to get the subjective feedback of emotional feelings and</p> <p style="top:636.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">analyze brain signals temporally localized to the feeling of an</p> <p style="top:648.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">emotion. We refer to these time-stamped emotional feelings</p> <p style="top:660.5pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">as ‘‘emotional events’’.</p> <p style="top:685.5pt;left:298.1pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>B. EXPERIMENTAL DETAILS</i></p> <p style="top:698.5pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:9.0pt">1) STIMULI</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">The selection of stimuli to induce participants’ emotions also</p> <p style="top:722.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">plays a vital role in emotion recognition. A careful selection</p> <p style="top:746.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:6.0pt">VOLUME 11, 2023</p> <p style="top:745.8pt;left:518.0pt;line-height:7.0pt">39915</p> <img src="/media/images/image_3_1.png" IfPe2Vftwd+k3eWvHQP6oqp7WS0sq7wrCK7xxwa5RhqkY3Gtbu2WBQN6IP01X/lV i/NtAetxTSeR1XFNcdafC9ckl2rBIFVpKJMw+7nm1eXbpAJnT54vdciVCNm5Rrme yeViMHDiSx0si7es3dJBsskyJSlr/B2TCAPkt3V9PyLW4xp5qesUq+Ka4rebAX35 aCgLp4xRYMp7JfcePhumg8U9XLtPVbE3gmwD7Guuq8pfe76VL6S2jsLZja59Y+2V axRNjs419us5gGvWbo55MHxKl2Tnm/VYWz7LidK6sf1i4Q+6u0jMx/S91yycrC0v CK7ZN9cUp3rI6TPuX1Jk6TAzdcl3PVkVmBPb11f+2ct3rCwl2X+jTfisMN0XeSKd FTHK2juQ3FlJzPzH2vn6E7VfOhmuGdATbx6IlZI6jOQa/XZIj8PdqSEUMybJYrBa OpjnOssd5RzoNvmkp7QiWTvbTDdzDwc5DRUOFDX9a5Msy/mWzIVTgPxmCpYV57US 9so1uazqSK7JxS/b4RppISv1ry4yWnLp26qOk9iSJCQ/tebk2+0WW1KslJQvO1dM 9W0W2CxtxlZL76whBpQZ+qX8Oa3b1kLUJUp15pphNpaLX4JrZrh7/goYqSUXfsm1 gCt2XcGOSxPNfWbKycdZ64zAKCAnPzf7Gb/rjEmTJGUwy7JasnrFmITG2SXdumXE xFyeKuFS87aVheu4Rvn6815ccM02uCbZpGa9RTnk45jcTGlngaefmpDCBmC6c4NR eRZKFKA0Q4B54Oh4pVNTcToEtpeunyJf7x2Dv+IQywapkK90hGG3I9kKi9riyRTS 4foW4/fcKTP6Ts6fxI9QOCkcv+BG5FRqC8TquEZ5uN+LC64ZyDW3fvd57kbI+rpV mzwZuebQ3eauWKva2Z2nmIbQe7vYh/SeLM0Scfq41MV2WdJnsahtEd6zaExwTfvI 1dHdffB4jAK5kDb5XWbVlcbkC1AJi3I9ECzD4vnPmZ2GYcllYJuexoZKzNhzZWa+ yHEBLkun8J7U8mG/MdTZk+fpuzWKa5RLcfvTL8fokEuQyzekbymt5YjFpKzSikkO CiXsdIn4AipVMUJVe/AG+fYm4ZZenEn5ljUVcv1oLMKNFyeHCUaLkZsWwEaxmgMb GEX1DF2NAQpgnF9kPx7nphe4j5xjhQdu7fVS5RHnVAgN446wvVxehlx6/LVn3QXs C55VmtfB/ntWJqG8T1J/kg+PDxs0fMbGlVE0Xw4covYUjMJxUiS8VvkkJhcpgcAu ABuD2ftOzhwAom+w+Zx1JmZ3ORESvkxpk3D311VwTSAQGIHgmkAgMALBNYFAYASC awKBwAgE1wQCgREIrgkEAiPwP1inMB/IgqkYAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC"> <p style="top:25.6pt;left:289.8pt;line-height:7.0pt">M. Asif et al.: Emotion Recognition Using Temporally Localized Emotional Events</p> <p style="top:65.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt"><b>TABLE 1.</b> Selected stimuli for EEG study from the stimuli dataset we</p> <p style="top:74.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">created [28]). The time duration of each stimulus is 60s. Stimulus Ids are</p> <p style="top:82.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">given for references available in the open science framework repository.</p> <p style="top:293.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">of stimuli is critical, and for that, technical validation of</p> <p style="top:305.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">the video clips is crucial to assess if the intended emotional</p> <p style="top:317.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">experience is elicited by the stimuli. We have used naturalistic</p> <p style="top:328.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">stimuli to elicit emotions in the participants. Naturalistic</p> <p style="top:340.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">stimuli are dynamic emotional scenes in which multi-sensory</p> <p style="top:352.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">perception is applied. It resembles more to the real-life</p> <p style="top:364.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">scenario as compared to static and simple stimuli. In our</p> <p style="top:376.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">previous work, we have validated a set of multimedia stimuli</p> <p style="top:388.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">and created an affective stimuli database [28]. We selected</p> <p style="top:400.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">16 emotional stimuli from this database to perform our EEG</p> <p style="top:412.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">experiment. The selection criteria for these 16 emotional</p> <p style="top:424.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">stimuli are based on three factors:</p> <p style="top:435.7pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">1) A high probability of eliciting target emotions (calcu-</p> <p style="top:447.6pt;left:60.4pt;line-height:10.0pt">lated on the basis of ratings available).</p> <p style="top:459.6pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">2) Few stimuli must be available for each emotion</p> <p style="top:471.6pt;left:60.4pt;line-height:10.0pt">category.</p> <p style="top:483.5pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">3) Since this experiment was done on the Indian popula-</p> <p style="top:495.5pt;left:60.4pt;line-height:10.0pt">tion, more emphasis was given to Indian clips.</p> <p style="top:506.4pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">Besides these 16 emotional stimuli, we have validated 2 non-</p> <p style="top:518.4pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">emotional stimuli separately. These clips were rated around</p> <p style="top:530.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">5 mean valence and arousal values (on a scale of 1 to 9).</p> <p style="top:542.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">These non-emotional clips included the world’s longest road</p> <p style="top:554.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">routes or animated history of the Babylonian era, which may</p> <p style="top:566.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">not contribute to eliciting emotions. The inclusion of non-</p> <p style="top:578.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">emotional stimuli was to validate the participants’ responses</p> <p style="top:590.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">and avoid the long accumulation of the affects during the</p> <p style="top:602.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">experiment.</p> <p style="top:614.0pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">For each participant, nine (9) emotional stimuli were</p> <p style="top:626.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">selected randomly from the 16 selected emotional stimuli</p> <p style="top:637.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">and two (2) non-emotional stimuli. Each stimulus was of</p> <p style="top:649.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">60 seconds.</p> <p style="top:661.8pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">Table 1 shows the list of 16 emotional stimuli with the</p> <p style="top:673.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">target emotions assigned during the stimuli validation.</p> <p style="top:698.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:9.0pt">2) EEG RECORDING</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">We</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:57.5pt;line-height:10.0pt">recorded</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:100.6pt;line-height:10.0pt">the</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:121.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">EEG</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:148.7pt;line-height:10.0pt">activity</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:186.7pt;line-height:10.0pt">of</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:203.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">forty</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:230.9pt;line-height:10.0pt">participants</p> <p style="top:722.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">(23<i>.</i>3 ± 1<i>.</i>25, F=3) while they were watching emotional film</p> <p style="top:65.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">stimuli. Following are some critical pieces of information</p> <p style="top:77.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">regarding the experiment:</p> <p style="top:90.8pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:7.6pt">• Each participant saw nine (9) emotional stimuli ran-</p> <p style="top:100.9pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">domly extracted from the set of 16 emotional stimuli</p> <p style="top:112.8pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">and two (2) non-emotional stimuli as described in the</p> <p style="top:124.8pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">previous subsection.</p> <p style="top:138.7pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:7.6pt">• While watching the emotional film stimuli, participants</p> <p style="top:148.7pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">were instructed to perform a mouse click the moment</p> <p style="top:160.7pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">they felt any emotion. We call it an Emotional Event.</p> <p style="top:174.5pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:7.6pt">• At the end of each video stimuli, participants are</p> <p style="top:184.6pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">provided six self-assessment scales, including valence,</p> <p style="top:196.5pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">arousal, dominance, liking, familiarity, and relevance.</p> <p style="top:210.4pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:7.6pt">• For each click, participants were supposed to select</p> <p style="top:220.4pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">one emotion from the provided list of emotions pooled</p> <p style="top:232.4pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">into four quadrants of V-A space (HVHA, LVHA,</p> <p style="top:244.3pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">LVLA, HVLA) (abbreviations- V: Valence, A: Arousal,</p> <p style="top:256.3pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">H: High, L: Low) in the drop-down menu. Participants</p> <p style="top:268.3pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">were also given a choice to enter the emotional category</p> <p style="top:280.2pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">which suits their emotional experience but is unavail-</p> <p style="top:292.2pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">able in the provided emotion list. For more details</p> <p style="top:304.1pt;left:316.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">see Fig.2.</p> <p style="top:316.0pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">Before the main experiment begins, participants go</p> <p style="top:328.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">through the training phase. In the training phase, participants</p> <p style="top:339.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">were given instructions about the experiment procedure,</p> <p style="top:351.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">rating scales were properly explained by giving them a small</p> <p style="top:363.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">quiz, and also they were trained to mouse-click when they felt</p> <p style="top:375.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">emotion during the stimulus.</p> <p style="top:387.8pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">The main experiment consists of the following steps for</p> <p style="top:399.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">each participant:</p> <p style="top:411.6pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">1) Baseline Recording: EEG signal was recorded for</p> <p style="top:423.6pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">80 seconds while the participant looked at the cross-</p> <p style="top:435.5pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">mark on the screen and performed no task.</p> <p style="top:447.5pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">2) After baseline recording, one stimulus of 60s was</p> <p style="top:459.5pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">presented to the participant. Participants were told to</p> <p style="top:471.4pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">click on the screen when they felt the emotion during</p> <p style="top:483.4pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">the stimulus. Participants may click more than once</p> <p style="top:495.3pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">if they felt so but were instructed to refrain from</p> <p style="top:507.3pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">multiple clicks for the same emotion. EEG signals were</p> <p style="top:519.2pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">recorded during this phase.</p> <p style="top:531.2pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">3) After the stimulus ends, participants go through self-</p> <p style="top:543.1pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">assessment ratings of valence, arousal, dominance,</p> <p style="top:555.1pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">liking, familiarity, and relevance. These scales are</p> <p style="top:567.0pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">explained in detail in the next subsection.</p> <p style="top:579.0pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">4) At last, participants were supposed to select one</p> <p style="top:591.0pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">emotion category for each click (emotional event).</p> <p style="top:602.9pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">To help the participants in recalling about the click, they</p> <p style="top:614.9pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">were presented with three frames around the click.</p> <p style="top:626.8pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">5) After this, an inter-stimulus interval comes with no</p> <p style="top:638.8pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">time limit. During this interval, participants were</p> <p style="top:650.7pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">given a quick and easy mathematical calculation (e.g.,</p> <p style="top:662.7pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">2+5*2=?). It helps participants to flush their previous</p> <p style="top:674.6pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">emotional state.</p> <p style="top:686.6pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">6) After that, the next stimulus is presented to the</p> <p style="top:698.6pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">participant, and steps 1 to 5 are followed similarly for</p> <p style="top:710.5pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">each stimulus. A total of 11 stimuli (9 emotional and</p> <p style="top:722.5pt;left:321.3pt;line-height:10.0pt">2 non-emotional) were presented to each participant.</p> <p style="top:745.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">39916</p> <p style="top:746.6pt;left:489.2pt;line-height:6.0pt">VOLUME 11, 2023</p> <img src="/media/images/image_4_1.png" alt="Image 1"><div id="page0" style="width:576.0pt;height:782.9pt"> <p style="top:25.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">M. EBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQ EBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQ EBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQ EBAQEBBUuFG9Q6OWWavna90dOTK8MALyGteSACWjPbIQUbRTSmj0yoI6+jLtR+sC 14DZGOacOY8AnDhyjPrjYgiKvhNt1HZau9OiqDBSzup3tDY+NLmyinJaOMDSNY52 kbOTOxB6/PGn+y7ee8U/45QSddppTWuW2x1cE8Ar8NjfI1gjjlc3WbBKQ8lsh3AY IJyMoPdeNK6az11FQFkk1RWOIZHEGuc1jRl8z9ZzQ2Mcp3k7ACUFfv3CvHo2JH1V murY2SCPjeJg4txLtRpaTUAkOO7YEF64LdKJL9XzsfbK+j1IC7Wqo4mNd1zBqt1J ZDnuINOQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQ YKlt2bxkb2NYGR/Wj5j9ZtiG06+vjV5t52AoKpwSsqaC41kF+1jeHwQOEkjg4PpA 1oa2MgAda/IlA3u25KCV4cvS6fkui8MxBruh36y3/dTvz5qC4oCAgICAgICAgICA gICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICA gICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICA gICAgICAgq3CXo63SyzTW54kLKjMb+KH1IGua4EjrXAHbygoKnVaGGutzrbPSyyQ OhELmuY7Jbq6u8AbeXI3HaEFaj4EqePR2XR7FeaeWTjHSHVNRrcY2b0XFavomje3 d3UH686O5erV/wC+Q/jZBIngzfPVW+pqTXVLqBhELZgHMMh2dMPAjbrS42A7hvAB 2oOi/wDB+dIZqOpfFUwz0cvGQzQt1ZBkYfGdZjgWOGxzSNqD9aV6BO0wouk6mKpY zjIpMxt1XZjcHtHXMcMZG3YguWilFPTVT3SRPYOLIy5paM6zdm0ILWgICAgICAgI CAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgI CAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgI CAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgIAP/Z"> <p style="top:376.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt"><b>FIGURE 2.</b> Emotion Category Selection Screen for Emotional Event (Click): After the participants rated all the six rating scales of Valence, Arousal,</p> <p style="top:384.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">Dominance, Liking, Familiarity and Relevance, they are shown this screen for emotion category selection. On this screen, three image frames were shown.</p> <p style="top:393.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">The middle one belongs to the time of the click; the left one is 20 frames earlier, and the right one is 20 frames after the click (Please note that the</p> <p style="top:401.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">stimulus clips were shown in 30 frames per second). It helps participants to recall easily. They only have to select one emotion category. If the</p> <p style="top:409.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">experienced emotion is not present in the list, they were free to write their own.</p> <p style="top:436.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:9.0pt">3) RATINGS</p> <p style="top:448.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">Subjective ratings are one of the well-known methods to eval-</p> <p style="top:460.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">uate the personal emotional experience of the participants.</p> <p style="top:472.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">Emotional pictures/videos or audio clips are presented to the</p> <p style="top:484.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">participants, and they are asked to rate these clips on different</p> <p style="top:496.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">scales based on their personal experiences. These scales</p> <p style="top:508.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">include Valence, Arousal, Dominance, Liking, Familiarity</p> <p style="top:520.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">and Relevance. The rating scales range from 1 to 9 for</p> <p style="top:532.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">Valence, Arousal and Dominance. For Liking, familiarity and</p> <p style="top:543.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">Relevance, it ranges from 1 to 5. Although, in this analysis,</p> <p style="top:555.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">we considered only valence and arousal scales.</p> <p style="top:590.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:9.0pt">4) SUMMARY OF THE EEG SIGNALS</p> <p style="top:603.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">As explained above, 465 emotional events were extracted</p> <p style="top:615.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">from the forty participants in this experiment. All the</p> <p style="top:627.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">participants clicked at least one time (average<b> 1.29</b> times)</p> <p style="top:638.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">during the stimulus.</p> <p style="top:650.9pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">Although for each participant and each stimulus, EEG</p> <p style="top:662.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">recording is available for the whole stimulus (i.e., for the</p> <p style="top:674.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">60s), we have considered the signal for 7 seconds duration</p> <p style="top:686.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">(1 second before the click and 6 seconds after the click) for</p> <p style="top:698.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">each emotional event. We have tested for other time durations</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">(e.g., 8s, 9s, up to 10s) but found better results with 7s</p> <p style="top:722.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">duration. The recording has a sampling rate of 250 Hz.</p> <p style="top:436.1pt;left:298.1pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>C. PREPROCESSING AND ARTIFACT REMOVAL</i></p> <p style="top:448.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>OF THE EEG DATA</i></p> <p style="top:460.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">The procedure followed to perform the preprocessing is</p> <p style="top:472.4pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">described elsewhere [29]. The critical step which should</p> <p style="top:484.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">be described here includes filtering and artifact removal.</p> <p style="top:496.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">We had 128-channel EEG raw data with a sampling rate</p> <p style="top:508.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">of 250 Hz. The raw signal is filtered using a Butterworth fifth-</p> <p style="top:520.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">order bandpass filter with the passband 1-40 Hz. Independent</p> <p style="top:532.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">component analysis (ICA) is used to remove artifacts,</p> <p style="top:544.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">including heart rate, muscle movement, and eye blink-related</p> <p style="top:556.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">artifacts.</p> <p style="top:590.9pt;left:298.1pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>D. OTHER DATASETS USED</i></p> <p style="top:603.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">We have used DEAP dataset [2] (a dataset for emotion</p> <p style="top:615.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">analysis using EEG, physiological and video signals) and</p> <p style="top:627.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">SEED dataset [3] (A dataset collection for various purposes</p> <p style="top:638.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">using EEG signals) for comparing the results with our dataset</p> <p style="top:650.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">(DENS).</p> <p style="top:662.8pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">The DEAP dataset consisted of 40 videos/trials, and for</p> <p style="top:674.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">each trial, there are 40 channels of EEG, including peripheral</p> <p style="top:686.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">signals, are available, and data is given for each channel.</p> <p style="top:698.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">We have used only 32 channels (i.e., discarded peripheral</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">signals) for the experiment as we only want to use data from</p> <p style="top:722.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">the brain only. This data was already preprocessed as 128 Hz</p> <p style="top:746.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:6.0pt">VOLUME 11, 2023</p> <p style="top:745.8pt;left:518.0pt;line-height:7.0pt">39917</p> <img aCgLp4xRYMp7JfcePhumg8U9XLtPVbE3gmwD7Guuq8pfe76VL6S2jsLZja59Y+2V axRNjs419us5gGvWbo55MHxKl2Tnm/VYWz7LidK6sf1i4Q+6u0jMx/S91yycrC0v CK7ZN9cUp3rI6TPuX1Jk6TAzdcl3PVkVmBPb11f+2ct3rCwl2X+jTfisMN0XeSKd FTHK2juQ3FlJzPzH2vn6E7VfOhmuGdATbx6IlZI6jOQa/XZIj8PdqSEUMybJYrBa OpjnOssd5RzoNvmkp7QiWTvbTDdzDwc5DRUOFDX9a5Msy/mWzIVTgPxmCpYV57US 9so1uazqSK7JxS/b4RppISv1ry4yWnLp26qOk9iSJCQ/tebk2+0WW1KslJQvO1dM 9W0W2CxtxlZL76whBpQZ+qX8Oa3b1kLUJUp15pphNpaLX4JrZrh7/goYqSUXfsm1 gCt2XcGOSxPNfWbKycdZ64zAKCAnPzf7Gb/rjEmTJGUwy7JasnrFmITG2SXdumXE xFyeKuFS87aVheu4Rvn6815ccM02uCbZpGa9RTnk45jcTGlngaefmpDCBmC6c4NR eRZKFKA0Q4B54Oh4pVNTcToEtpeunyJf7x2Dv+IQywapkK90hGG3I9kKi9riyRTS 4foW4/fcKTP6Ts6fxI9QOCkcv+BG5FRqC8TquEZ5uN+LC64ZyDW3fvd57kbI+rpV mzwZuebQ3eauWKva2Z2nmIbQe7vYh/SeLM0Scfq41MV2WdJnsahtEd6zaExwTfvI 1dHdffB4jAK5kDb5XWbVlcbkC1AJi3I9ECzD4vnPmZ2GYcllYJuexoZKzNhzZWa+ yHEBLkun8J7U8mG/MdTZk+fpuzWKa5RLcfvTL8fokEuQyzekbymt5YjFpKzSikkO CiXsdIn4AipVMUJVe/AG+fYm4ZZenEn5ljUVcv1oLMKNFyeHCUaLkZsWwEaxmgMb GEX1DF2NAQpgnF9kPx7nphe4j5xjhQdu7fVS5RHnVAgN446wvVxehlx6/LVn3QXs C55VmtfB/ntWJqG8T1J/kg+PDxs0fMbGlVE0Xw4covYUjMJxUiS8VvkkJhcpgcAu ABuD2ftOzhwAom+w+Zx1JmZ3ORESvkxpk3D311VwTSAQGIHgmkAgMALBNYFAYASC awKBwAgE1wQCgREIrgkEAiPwP1inMB/IgqkYAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC"> <p style="top:25.6pt;left:289.8pt;line-height:7.0pt">M. Asif et al.: Emotion Recognition Using Temporally Localized Emotional Events</p> <p style="top:65.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">downsampled, bandpass frequency of 4-45 Hz and EOG</p> <p style="top:77.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">removed. For each trial, there are 4 labels available- Valence</p> <p style="top:89.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">(V), Arousal (A), Dominance and Linking. We have used only</p> <p style="top:100.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">V-A space for the experiment purpose.</p> <p style="top:112.9pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">The SEED dataset was recorded for 15 participants,</p> <p style="top:124.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">and emotions were presented to the participants into three</p> <p style="top:136.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">categories- positive, negative and neutral emotions (i.e., only</p> <p style="top:148.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">valence (V) values were used). We have used only V-space in</p> <p style="top:160.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">the DENS dataset to match the number of classes for both the</p> <p style="top:172.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">datasets. The data was recorded using 62 channels.</p> <p style="top:196.5pt;left:37.2pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>E. SOME SALIENT FEATURES OF THE DENS</i></p> <p style="top:208.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">To sum up, we are highlighting some key points of our</p> <p style="top:220.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">dataset-</p> <p style="top:232.6pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:7.6pt">• To the best of our knowledge, the first time, we created</p> <p style="top:242.7pt;left:55.9pt;line-height:10.0pt">a dataset on Emotion with Naturalistic Stimuli (DENS)</p> <p style="top:254.6pt;left:55.9pt;line-height:10.0pt">and recorded EEG signals from participants in the Indian</p> <p style="top:266.6pt;left:55.9pt;line-height:10.0pt">subcontinent.</p> <p style="top:280.4pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:7.6pt">• Stimuli that are used to record EEG data of the</p> <p style="top:290.5pt;left:55.9pt;line-height:10.0pt">participants are pre-validated on a different set of</p> <p style="top:302.4pt;left:55.9pt;line-height:10.0pt">participants for the selected emotion categories.</p> <p style="top:316.3pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:7.6pt">• Participants were free to select any emotion category,</p> <p style="top:326.3pt;left:55.9pt;line-height:10.0pt">whatever they felt for the stimuli from the given list.</p> <p style="top:340.2pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:7.6pt">• We used 128-channel high-density EEG recording for</p> <p style="top:350.3pt;left:55.9pt;line-height:10.0pt">higher spatial resolution.</p> <p style="top:364.1pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:7.6pt">•<b> Emotional Event:</b> Temporal markers are available</p> <p style="top:374.2pt;left:55.9pt;line-height:10.0pt">for each emotion category when participants feel the</p> <p style="top:386.1pt;left:55.9pt;line-height:10.0pt">emotion, resulting in higher temporal resolution.</p> <p style="top:408.1pt;left:37.2pt;line-height:9.0pt"><b>III. METHODOLOGY</b></p> <p style="top:420.1pt;left:37.2pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>A. FEATURE EXTRACTION</i></p> <p style="top:432.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">EEG Signals are non-stationary, meaning the signal’s sta-</p> <p style="top:444.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">tistical characteristics change over time. If these signals</p> <p style="top:456.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">are transformed to the frequency domain using Fourier</p> <p style="top:468.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">Transform, it provides the frequency information, which is</p> <p style="top:480.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">averaged over the entire EEG signal. So, information on</p> <p style="top:492.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">different frequency events is not analyzed properly. If a</p> <p style="top:503.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">signal is cut into minor segments such that it could be</p> <p style="top:515.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">considered as stationary and focus on signal properties at a</p> <p style="top:527.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">particular section which is called a windowing section and</p> <p style="top:539.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">apply Fourier transform on it, it is called as Short-Time</p> <p style="top:551.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">Fourier Transform (STFT). It will move to the entire signal</p> <p style="top:563.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">length and apply Fourier transform to find the spectral content</p> <p style="top:575.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">of that section and display the coefficient as a function of</p> <p style="top:587.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">both time and frequency. It provides insight into the nature of</p> <p style="top:599.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">the time-varying spectral characteristics of the signal. Before</p> <p style="top:611.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">STFT, let’s look at the discrete Fourier transform. Consider</p> <p style="top:623.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">x: [0: L-1] = {0<i>,</i> 1<i>, . . . ,</i><i> L</i> −1} →R be a discrete-time signal</p> <p style="top:635.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">where L is the signal length which is acquired by equidistance</p> <p style="top:647.4pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">sample points with respect to the fixed sampling frequency.</p> <p style="top:659.4pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">Mathematically DFT equation is,</p> <p style="top:685.3pt;left:102.5pt;line-height:10.0pt">b<i>x</i>(<i>k</i>) =</p> <p style="top:674.7pt;left:133.9pt;line-height:7.6pt"><i>N</i>−1</p> <p style="top:675.9pt;left:134.6pt;line-height:10.0pt">X</p> <p style="top:699.6pt;left:135.0pt;line-height:7.6pt"><i>n</i>=0</p> <p style="top:685.3pt;left:151.2pt;line-height:10.0pt"><i>x</i>(<i>n</i>)<i>.</i><i>e</i><sup>−</sup><sup><i>i</i></sup><sup>2</sup><sup><i>π</i></sup><sup><i>nk</i></sup><sup><i>/</i></sup><sup><i>N</i></sup></p> <p style="top:685.3pt;left:265.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">(1)</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">where k<i> ϵ</i> [0, K] and K is the frequency index with respect</p> <p style="top:722.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">to Nyquist frequency. N is the duration of the section. The</p> <p style="top:65.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">equation returns the complex Fourier coefficients for the</p> <p style="top:77.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">k<sup><i>th</i></sup>. These coefficients provide two parameters: phase and</p> <p style="top:89.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">magnitude. For STFT, consider the additional parameter hop</p> <p style="top:100.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">size (H), which is the step size of the window to be shifted.</p> <p style="top:112.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt"><i>ω</i> be a sampling window function which is<i> ω</i>: [0, N-1] →R.</p> <p style="top:124.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">STFT can be defined as,</p> <p style="top:149.8pt;left:332.9pt;line-height:10.0pt"><i>S</i>(<i>m</i><i>,</i><i> k</i>) :=</p> <p style="top:139.2pt;left:378.7pt;line-height:7.6pt"><i>N</i>−1</p> <p style="top:140.4pt;left:379.5pt;line-height:10.0pt">X</p> <p style="top:164.1pt;left:379.8pt;line-height:7.6pt"><i>n</i>=0</p> <p style="top:149.8pt;left:396.0pt;line-height:10.0pt"><i>x</i>(<i>n</i> +<i> mH</i>)<i>ω</i>(<i>n</i>)<i>e</i><sup>(</sup><sup>−</sup><sup><i>i</i></sup><sup>2</sup><sup><i>π</i></sup><sup><i>kn</i></sup><sup><i>/</i></sup><sup><i>N</i></sup><sup>)</sup></p> <p style="top:149.8pt;left:526.7pt;line-height:10.0pt">(2)</p> <p style="top:175.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">where m<i> ϵ</i> [0,M] and M is the maximum frame index</p> <p style="top:186.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">mathematically M =</p> <p style="top:178.9pt;left:395.8pt;line-height:10.0pt"><i> L</i>−<i>N</i></p> <p style="top:192.4pt;left:407.2pt;line-height:7.6pt"><i>H</i></p> <p style="top:178.9pt;left:419.8pt;line-height:10.0pt"></p> <p style="top:186.9pt;left:424.8pt;line-height:10.0pt">. The Short-Time Fourier</p> <p style="top:198.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">Transform is not only a function of k but also m which is a</p> <p style="top:210.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">proxy time representation. Here, the function returns Fourier</p> <p style="top:222.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">coefficients for the k<sup><i>th</i></sup><sup> </sup>proxy frequency at the m<sup><i>th</i></sup><sup> </sup>temporal</p> <p style="top:234.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">bin.</p> <p style="top:246.7pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">Spectrograms are nothing but the squared magnitude of</p> <p style="top:258.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">STFT of the signal.</p> <p style="top:275.4pt;left:374.4pt;line-height:10.0pt"><i>χ</i>(<i>m</i><i>,</i><i> k</i>) := |<i>S</i>(<i>m</i><i>,</i><i> k</i>)|<sup>2</sup></p> <p style="top:275.4pt;left:526.7pt;line-height:10.0pt">(3)</p> <p style="top:292.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">It is a 2D image where the horizontal axis represents time,</p> <p style="top:304.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">and the vertical axis represents frequency bins. The number</p> <p style="top:316.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">of frequency bins is (framesize / 2) + 1 and the number of</p> <p style="top:328.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">time frames is ((size of signal – framesize) / hopsize) + 1.</p> <p style="top:340.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt"><i>χ</i>(<i>m</i><i>,</i><i> k</i>) represents intensity or color at (m, k).</p> <p style="top:363.7pt;left:298.1pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>B. INPUT PREPROCESSING TO FEED DATA INTO THE</i></p> <p style="top:375.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>CLASSIFIER</i></p> <p style="top:387.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">It is essential to convert the data into a meaningful format that</p> <p style="top:399.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">can be fed into our classifier model. As all three datasets are</p> <p style="top:411.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">available in different formats, we have provided information</p> <p style="top:423.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">on the input preprocessing for each dataset as follows:</p> <p style="top:447.4pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:9.0pt">1) FOR DEAP DATA</p> <p style="top:459.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">Each subject in the DEAP dataset is given by a tensor</p> <p style="top:471.5pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">that is in the form of X ∈R<sup>40</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>40</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>8064</sup>, representing</p> <p style="top:483.5pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">40 videos, 40 EEG-channels (including peripheral channels),</p> <p style="top:495.4pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">and 8064 EEG data samples for each channel. For labels,</p> <p style="top:507.4pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">DEAP data provided a matrix in the form of X ∈R<sup>40</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>4</sup>;</p> <p style="top:519.4pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">i.e., for each subject, there are 40 videos and 4 scales. From</p> <p style="top:531.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">the DEAP dataset, the first 15 subjects are picked. For the</p> <p style="top:543.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">label, we used the Valence-Arousal space and divided it into</p> <p style="top:555.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">four classes- HVHA, HVLA, LVLA, LVHA (abbreviations-</p> <p style="top:567.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">H: High, L: Low, V: Valence, A: Arousal). The ratings for</p> <p style="top:579.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">valence and arousal range from 1 to 9. Hence, we considered</p> <p style="top:591.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">ratings from 1 to 5 as ‘Low’ and 5 to 9 as ‘High’ and divided</p> <p style="top:603.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">the V-A space into 4 quadrants accordingly.</p> <p style="top:615.0pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">We converted 15 subjects’ data tensor into a matrix</p> <p style="top:627.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">of X ∈R<sup>19200</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>8064</sup><sup> </sup>(<i>i</i><i>.</i><i>e</i><i>.,</i> 15<i> subjects</i> × 40<i> videos</i> ×</p> <p style="top:638.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">32<i> channels</i><i>,</i> 8064<i> samples</i>). Moreover, this data was pro-</p> <p style="top:650.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">cessed for feature extraction using STFT with a window size</p> <p style="top:662.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">of 0.5s and an overlap of 0.25s of data samples. Using STFT,</p> <p style="top:674.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">we have converted every 8064 sizes of EEG data samples</p> <p style="top:686.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">into a spectrogram image size of (33,251), as mentioned in</p> <p style="top:698.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">the feature extraction section. Then, a hybrid CNN-LSTM</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">classifier was implemented for multi-class classification with</p> <p style="top:722.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">an input tensor of X ∈R<sup>33</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>251</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>3</sup>.</p> <p style="top:745.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">39918</p> <p style="top:746.6pt;left:489.2pt;line-height:6.0pt">VOLUME 11, 2023</p> <img src="/media/images/image_6_1.png" alt="Image 1"><div id="page0" style="width:576.0pt;height:782.9pt"> <p style="top:25.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">M. AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAACueFzgjhpnCOIw8uRx9HbRrL4eTnbfB+/q3urptP8zF+D5Ym HGJTNMxeJ3j7OdV2iWls8bOeCxsORx1F2q0n6cd94PY7q+9bWmm+Wqm3BnWeyM5a nCOIw8uRx9HbRrL4eTnbfB+/q3urptP8zF+D5YmHGJTNMxeJ3j7OdV2iWls8dOeC xsORx1F2q0n6cd94PY7q+9bWmm+Wqm3BnWeyM5aq8caZ2n5p60pPkhZgPy/L+AAB 6PxiMPHFRcJpOLTTTV0096afQekVWm8bxtKr8Rh6vBnU1o608tnLatspUJP43Tbf /o+d+/C7flWOmqM9HNGLEeauI+f7OyxcvxccWozptSjJJpramuhryH4ieKBxKbX5 p546HpcVvxGY/wB/bEejTO+PmhquU8TR5NP9RhdZ+nYAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAVzwt8EcNM4RxGHlyOPo7aNZfDyc7b4P39W91dNp/ mYvwfLEw4xKZpmLxO8fZzqw0Q0qqZhOeCxdN0cdQ2VqT9OO+8HsaavvW1ppvkqpt Nmc57Izlqummdp+aetKlRb6GfjRKEk7nl1M90S8udzy6mNElzueXUxokHh5dTGmX jjxGBWJi6dSOtGSaaaumnvT8h5NMkVTTN43jaVZPA1uDGspRUqmWTlt3ylh23vfT ye36dttb92vx5/lT+qM9TzRixHZFcR/dvs7LM4qGKji8JjqsHeM80ryT604U2viO qPmhoOXp04VETvFMXjzQvA/boAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAEK084IsDprKNXEKcK8FaFajN0q0V1ayumvI07XdrXZ5u/FVMVRaYiY6J4 oe+LFh3/ACIZl+Ux/cz8aez0Ph3Nh/Ao+LB+hhw33QzL8pj+5jR2eh73NhfAo+LB +hhw33QzL8pj+5jR2eg7mwvgUfFg/Qw4b7oZl+Ux/cxo7PQdzYXwKPiwfoYcN90M y/KY/uY0dnoO5sL4FHxYP0MWH+6GZflMf3M80dnoO5sL4FHxYcWK4q2DxcXCrjsx nFqzUsRBprqs6TR+opt949jL4dPGKKInmmKY4J3wY8GOG4OMNLB4OVSUJVZVG6jj KWs4xi+bGKtaK6D9OhL7HoAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAP/Z"> <p style="top:255.3pt;left:41.7pt;line-height:7.0pt"><b>FIGURE 3.</b> Model Architecture: It is consisted of two 2D-convolution layers with 3<b> ×</b> 3 kernels and 32 filters and 64 filters respectively, followed by a</p> <p style="top:263.7pt;left:41.7pt;line-height:7.0pt">max pooling layer followed by a dropout layer and flattening layer. A repeat vector layer of size 4 is used before sending the data to the LSTM layers.</p> <p style="top:272.1pt;left:41.7pt;line-height:7.0pt">Two LSTM layers are used of sizes 256 units and 128 units respectively, each followed by a dropout layer. At the end, two dense layers are used of</p> <p style="top:280.4pt;left:41.7pt;line-height:7.0pt">sizes 64 (followed by a dropout layer) and 4 or 3 (equals the number of the output classes).</p> <p style="top:306.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:9.0pt">2) FOR SEED DATA</p> <p style="top:318.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">SEED dataset contains 45.mat files for 15 subjects for each</p> <p style="top:330.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">subject with 3 trials. The label file contains 3 emotional</p> <p style="top:342.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">labels −1 for negative, 0 for neutral, and 1 for positive on</p> <p style="top:354.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">the valence scale. After renaming, the labels become 0 for</p> <p style="top:366.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">neutral, 1 for positive, and 2 for negative. For classification,</p> <p style="top:378.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">we have considered 15.mat files, one trial per subject. Due</p> <p style="top:390.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">to the different sizes of data length in each channel, the</p> <p style="top:402.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">first 16000 sample for each data which is the first 80s of</p> <p style="top:414.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">data, is considered for further processing. EEG cap includes</p> <p style="top:426.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">62 channels according to the 10-20 international system.</p> <p style="top:438.4pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">So, 15 subjects, 15 trials, 62-channels, and 16000 EEG</p> <p style="top:450.4pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">data are converted into a tensor of X ∈R<sup>13950</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>16000</sup></p> <p style="top:462.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">(<i>i</i><i>.</i><i>e</i><i>.,</i> 15<i> subjects</i>×15<i> trials</i>×62<i> channels</i><i>,</i> 16000<i> samples</i>)for</p> <p style="top:474.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">feature extraction. As mentioned in the DEAP dataset</p> <p style="top:486.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">experiment, using STFT with a window size of 0.5s and</p> <p style="top:498.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">overlap of 0.25s, each 16000 EEG data is converted into</p> <p style="top:510.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">a spectrogram with the shape of (51,319). Then, a hybrid</p> <p style="top:522.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">CNN-LSTM classifier was implemented for multi-class</p> <p style="top:534.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">classification with input tensor shape X ∈R<sup>51</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>319</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>3</sup>.</p> <p style="top:567.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:9.0pt">3) FOR DENS DATA</p> <p style="top:579.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">For the DENS dataset, we have 465.mat files which</p> <p style="top:591.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">contain emotional events. All 465 files are picked for the</p> <p style="top:603.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">experiment. Each.mat file is a matrix of X ∈R<sup>128</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>1751</sup>,</p> <p style="top:615.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">where 128 is the number of EEG channels and 1751 is</p> <p style="top:627.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">the sample data for each channel. Then we have con-</p> <p style="top:638.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">verted the data tensor of X ∈R<sup>465</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>128</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>1751</sup><sup> </sup>into the</p> <p style="top:650.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">form of R<sup>59520</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>1751</sup></p> <p style="top:650.9pt;left:134.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">(<i>i</i><i>.</i><i>e</i><i>.,</i> 465</p> <p style="top:650.9pt;left:183.8pt;line-height:10.0pt"><i>emotional</i></p> <p style="top:650.9pt;left:238.2pt;line-height:10.0pt"><i>events</i> ×</p> <p style="top:662.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">128<i> channels</i><i>,</i> 1751<i> samples</i>) for feature extraction with win-</p> <p style="top:674.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">dow size 0.5s and overlap is 0.25s. After feature extraction,</p> <p style="top:686.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">we have 59520 spectrograms, and each spectrogram is in the</p> <p style="top:698.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">shape of (63, 26).</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">To compare with the DEAP dataset, the DENS dataset with</p> <p style="top:722.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">4-label classification is performed with a hybrid CNN-LSTM</p> <p style="top:305.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">classifier. For the label, we used the same V-A space</p> <p style="top:317.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">(HVHA, HVLA, LVLA, LVHA) (abbreviations- H: High,</p> <p style="top:329.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">L: Low, V: Valence, A: Arousal) as it was used with the</p> <p style="top:341.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">DEAP dataset. The ratings for valence and arousal range</p> <p style="top:353.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">from 1 to 9. Hence, we considered ratings from 1 to 5 as</p> <p style="top:365.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">‘Low’ and 5 to 9 as ‘High’ and divided the V-A space into</p> <p style="top:377.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">4 quadrants accordingly. The dimension of input tensor is</p> <p style="top:389.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">of X ∈R<sup>63</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>26</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>3</sup>.</p> <p style="top:401.6pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">To compare with the SEED dataset, we have used a 3-label</p> <p style="top:413.5pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">classification since there are only three classes available in</p> <p style="top:425.5pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">SEED dataset. For the DENS dataset, on the valence scale,</p> <p style="top:437.4pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">ratings below 4.5 are marked as negative (0 labelled), and</p> <p style="top:449.4pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">ratings above 5.5 are marked as positive (2 labelled). For</p> <p style="top:461.4pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">neutral labels, in the DENS dataset, we have non-emotional</p> <p style="top:473.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">files; we have marked neutral (1 labelled) for those files’ data.</p> <p style="top:485.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">Then with the classifier, the input tensor of X ∈R<sup>63</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>26</sup><sup>×</sup><sup>3</sup><sup> </sup>is</p> <p style="top:497.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">used for classification.</p> <p style="top:531.1pt;left:298.1pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>C. MODEL ARCHITECTURE FOR THE</i></p> <p style="top:543.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>CLASSIFICATION TASK</i></p> <p style="top:555.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) and Long Short-Term</p> <p style="top:567.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">Memory (LSTM) are one of the most widely used deep</p> <p style="top:579.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">learning techniques. CNNs are used to extract meaningful</p> <p style="top:591.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">patterns and features from the data. The key element in CNN</p> <p style="top:603.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">is the convolution operation using kernels that automatically</p> <p style="top:615.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">learn the local patterns from data. These local features are</p> <p style="top:627.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">then combined into more complex features when multiple</p> <p style="top:638.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">CNN layers are stacked. Filters (i.e, weights trained) in</p> <p style="top:650.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">this process are also known as feature detector matrices.</p> <p style="top:662.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">Input data will be convoluted with a filter map by sliding</p> <p style="top:674.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">the kernel window. At the same time, LSTM networks can</p> <p style="top:686.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">capture the sequential pattern as LSTMs are best suited for</p> <p style="top:698.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">time-series data. LSTMs are designed to work for temporal</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">correlations. Therefore, to exploit the benefits of both CNN</p> <p style="top:722.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">and LSTM, a hybrid CNN-LSTM architecture is used for</p> <p style="top:746.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:6.0pt">VOLUME 11, 2023</p> <p style="top:745.8pt;left:518.0pt;line-height:7.0pt">39919</p> <img src="/media/images/image_7_1.png" alt="Image 1"><img mTfddFNeXp4EL+eDL563gwsKCpo0aeJExp07d8pDc95ffuSRR3x+HLCMiTAlJcX7 wJEjR8rmHXfcMbgEvI/dvn27PEaJg6GhoXLU9ddfv3nz5ss+QAB/h0QIAFAlSEtL K+V1LO83PSvyrnHnzp1lfM+ePd6D77zzjneuOn/+/FVXXSWhTaKb97Tf/e53rhOh 0Lp166DCn9JzPsgcFRXl2bVv3z4ZiYmJ8TmkX79+pSfCL7/8Mqi4r7YZMmSI94FP PvmkbD7zzDNlWaeHc+fOTZgwIajwBxDLdSCAP0IiBACoEjz88MMSPiZNmlR0l5PY IiIinE3nPVD5s5SzOcnv0KFDPuMPPPBA0H//ZN53P3xkxJMInZgVHR3tPScvLy8s LKwiiXDBggVBhZ+bHjRokNyYPXu2Z9fmzZtlJCEhwXv+119/7XwXTCmJ8MKFC9Wq VZNpFy9e9F6q82OLngO3bt0aVPil32VZpze5ubnBwcE1a9Ys74EAfgeJEABAH88b qR999FHRvZcuXWrQoIHsTUtL+67wHVjn22defvllz5yCgoKNGzd6PpLiZLXU1FSf Uy1evFjG4+LinG8BFN58881rr73WOxFKuqpVq5ac3/NBEFme82pZRRLhV199JeeU lcvdXXXVVZI7PbtOnz4tIzfccMPBgwedkZycHM+P9JWSCIX27dvLyPz58z2Lf+ih h4oe6ETkMWPGnDt3zntVO3fu9Hz7zLJly3xePV2zZk1QBX67NIAfQSIEANDn9ddf Lz15TJw4Majw6/SczZdeeikkJCSo8IOx999/f7du3TzfUO1MWL16tWxKxurTp8+D hTjj2dnZzte+3HLLLb17927Tpo1EsUmTJvn8NN6MGTNk5Oqrr3a+obphw4Y1a9Yc O3ZsRRKhcM899zhZTU7rs2vEiBEyLvfSo0cPWbPk47p16/q8+ftdcYlw06ZN8hBk MDY2NjExUR6XHOgszOcbqp1vva5du3bHjh0HDBggd+Q8aZ5n1flYd6NGjRISEvr3 79+2bdvg4GA5+cqVK8v4AAH8FxIhAIA+kj98wpYPzte1/OhHP/K8Pbpr165BgwY1 aNBAoqGMt2vXbs6cOd5vns6bN0/yovOrTYKC/lPtjx8/LndXp04diV8xMTGrVq0q 9vMZL774okSoa6655qabbpKoJHcnAauCiXDFihXOYuTkPrvy8/Nl/bLgGjVqSBwc OHDgkSNHin7RdLE/H5mamtqqVSt5pDfeeGNSUpLsLfa32OXk5CxYsCAuLq5WrVqh oaESB+Vss2fPPnbsmDPh3XffldQbHR0tD1mW8fOf/1zStjzzZXx0AH4NiRAAAADA dkiEAAAAALZDIgQAAACwHRIhAAAAgO2QCAEAAABsh0QIAAAAYDskQgAAAADbIREC AAAA2A6JEAAAAMB2SIQAAAAAtkMiBAAAALAdEiEAAACA7ZAIAQAAAGyHRAgAAABg OyRCAAAAANv5f2Jg9nALu+ZdAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC"> <p style="top:255.4pt;left:51.7pt;line-height:7.0pt"><b>FIGURE 4.</b> Comparison of Confusion matrices for DEAP and DENS datasets over Valence-Arousal space. This space is divided into four classes</p> <p style="top:263.8pt;left:51.7pt;line-height:7.0pt">and assigned a label to it (0-HVHA, 1-HVLA, 2-LVHA and 3-LVLA). 4a: DEAP Dataset; 4b: DENS Dataset. Abbreviations of the terms- V:Valence;</p> <p style="top:272.2pt;left:51.7pt;line-height:7.0pt">A:Arousal; L:Low; H:High. The color bar represents the number of samples in the class.</p> <p style="top:303.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">the classification of emotions. The hybrid CNN-LSTM</p> <p style="top:315.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">model utilizes the ability of convolutional layers for feature</p> <p style="top:327.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">extraction from data, and LSTM layers are for long-term and</p> <p style="top:339.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">short-term dependencies. The same model is used to compare</p> <p style="top:351.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">all three datasets. The model classifier and its details are</p> <p style="top:363.4pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">shown in Fig. 3.</p> <p style="top:375.4pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">CNN is often placed in the initial layers as it helps in local</p> <p style="top:387.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">pattern learning from spectrogram or in general input data.</p> <p style="top:399.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">The Pattern learning block consists of two 2D-convolutional</p> <p style="top:411.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">blocks, each with a kernel size of (3 × 3). The feature map,</p> <p style="top:423.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">which is the output of convolutional layers, keeps track of</p> <p style="top:435.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">the location of the features in the input. A max-Pooling</p> <p style="top:447.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">layer is added in between two consecutive convolutional</p> <p style="top:459.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">layers. A pooling layer is added after the convolutional layer</p> <p style="top:471.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">to reduce the feature-map dimension; hence it reduces the</p> <p style="top:483.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">computational cost, and the activation function is applied</p> <p style="top:494.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">to enhance the capability of the model. Rectified Linear</p> <p style="top:506.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">Unit (ReLU) activation function which has been widely</p> <p style="top:518.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">used to resilient vanishing gradient problem. In between, the</p> <p style="top:530.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">dropout layer is used in some places to avoid the overfitting</p> <p style="top:542.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">problem. The flattening layer transforms these feature maps</p> <p style="top:554.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">into one-dimensional vectors. The repeat vector gives extra</p> <p style="top:566.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">dimension for the LSTM layer. The sequential learning block</p> <p style="top:578.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">consists of 2 LSTM layers which capture the long-term</p> <p style="top:590.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">temporal dependencies from the feature map extracted by</p> <p style="top:602.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">CNN layers. 1<sup><i>st</i></sup><sup> </sup>LSTM layer consists of 256 cells with a</p> <p style="top:614.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">return sequence set to ‘True’ while 2<sup><i>nd</i></sup><sup> </sup>LSTM consists of</p> <p style="top:626.4pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">128 cells and as it is the last LSTM layer return sequence</p> <p style="top:638.4pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">is ‘False’. Between LSTM layers, dropout layers with rate =</p> <p style="top:650.4pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">0.2 are added to avoid overfitting issues. Finally, two fully-</p> <p style="top:662.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">connected layers where 1<sup><i>st</i></sup><sup> </sup>layer with 64 neurons and 2<sup><i>nd</i></sup></p> <p style="top:674.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">layer with the number of classes as neurons are added for</p> <p style="top:686.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">further processing. As we have the multi-class classification,</p> <p style="top:698.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">the SoftMax activation function is used in the output layer as</p> <p style="top:710.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">it outputs a vector representing the probability distributions</p> <p style="top:722.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">of a list of potential classes.</p> <p style="top:304.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:7.0pt"><b>TABLE 2.</b> Parameter Settings for the Model.</p> <p style="top:425.4pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">The parameter setting for the developed deep learning</p> <p style="top:437.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">model is mentioned in Table 2.</p> <p style="top:466.7pt;left:298.1pt;line-height:9.0pt"><b>IV. RESULTS</b></p> <p style="top:477.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">The confusion matrix for DEAP, SEED and DENS datasets</p> <p style="top:489.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">are shown in Fig. 4 and Fig. 5. In the confusion matrix</p> <p style="top:501.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">shown, each cell contains data on the number of population.</p> <p style="top:513.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">The X-axis represents actual labels and the Y-axis represents</p> <p style="top:525.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">predicted labels by the classifier. The diagonal of the</p> <p style="top:537.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">matrix represents the correctly identified label. The color bar</p> <p style="top:549.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">represents the number of samples in the class.</p> <p style="top:578.9pt;left:298.1pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>A. COMPARISON BETWEEN DEAP AND DENS</i></p> <p style="top:591.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">We have used repeated K-Fold cross-validation with</p> <p style="top:603.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">K = 5 and the number of repeats = 5 so generated</p> <p style="top:615.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">25 accuracies for DENS and DEAP. For label classification,</p> <p style="top:627.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">we have used V-A space (HVHA, HVLA, LVLA, LVHA).</p> <p style="top:638.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">Comparison between DEAP and DENS is mentioned in</p> <p style="top:650.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">Table 4. The loss and accuracy graphs are mentioned in Fig. 8.</p> <p style="top:662.8pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">Fig. 6 shows an F1 score comparison between DEAP</p> <p style="top:674.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">and DENS datasets per trial. Using t-test statistical test-</p> <p style="top:686.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">ing, the 25 F1 scores of DEAP dataset (M = 95.65%,</p> <p style="top:698.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">SD = 0.38%) compared with the 25 F1 scores of DENS</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">dataset (M = 96.82%, SD = 0.18%), DENS dataset shows</p> <p style="top:722.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">better results with absolute t (35) = 13.54,<i> p</i><i> &lt;</i> 0<i>.</i>0001,</p> <p style="top:745.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">39920</p> <p style="top:746.6pt;left:489.2pt;line-height:6.0pt">VOLUME 11, 2023</p> <img src="/media/images/image_8_1.png" alt="Image 1"><img src="/media/images/image_8_2.png" alt="Image 2"><img src="/media/images/image_8_3.png" alt="Image 3"><img src="/media/images/image_8_4.png" alt="Image 4"><img src="/media/images/image_8_5.png" alt="Image 5"><img src="/media/images/image_8_6.png" alt="Image 6"><img src="/media/images/image_8_7.png" alt="Image 7"><div id="page0" style="width:576.0pt;height:782.9pt"> <p style="top:25.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">M. style="top:255.4pt;left:51.7pt;line-height:7.0pt"><b>FIGURE 5.</b> Comparison of Confusion matrices for SEED and DENS datasets over Valence space. This space is divided into three classes (SEED</p> <p style="top:263.8pt;left:51.7pt;line-height:7.0pt">dataset provided data with three classes, while DENS data is divided into three classes based on the valence ratings provided by the</p> <p style="top:272.2pt;left:51.7pt;line-height:7.0pt">participants) and assigned a label to it as follows: For SEED:0 for neutral, 1 for positive and 2 for negative. For DENS: 0 for low-valence (valence</p> <p style="top:280.5pt;left:51.7pt;line-height:7.0pt">ratings range from 1-4.5), 1 for non-emotional data (valence ratings range from 4.5-5.5, as well as neutral categories stimuli) and 2 for</p> <p style="top:288.9pt;left:51.7pt;line-height:7.0pt">high-valence (valence ratings ranges from 5.5-9). 5a: SEED Dataset; 5b: DENS Dataset. The color bar represents the number of samples in the</p> <p style="top:297.3pt;left:51.7pt;line-height:7.0pt">class.</p> <p style="top:315.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt"><b>TABLE 3.</b> Comparison Table with Other Recent Studies.</p> <p style="top:685.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt"><b>FIGURE 6.</b> F1 scores of DEAP vs DENS for all the 25 trials.</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">d estimate: −13.70 (large), 95 percent confidence interval:</p> <p style="top:722.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">[−16.51 −10.89].</p> <p style="top:546.5pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:7.0pt"><b>TABLE 4.</b> DEAP vs DENS with mean F1 scores.</p> <p style="top:613.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:7.0pt"><b>TABLE 5.</b> SEED vs DENS with mean F1 scores.</p> <p style="top:674.6pt;left:298.1pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>B. aCgLp4xRYMp7JfcePhumg8U9XLtPVbE3gmwD7Guuq8pfe76VL6S2jsLZja59Y+2V axRNjs419us5gGvWbo55MHxKl2Tnm/VYWz7LidK6sf1i4Q+6u0jMx/S91yycrC0v CK7ZN9cUp3rI6TPuX1Jk6TAzdcl3PVkVmBPb11f+2ct3rCwl2X+jTfisMN0XeSKd FTHK2juQ3FlJzPzH2vn6E7VfOhmuGdATbx6IlZI6jOQa/XZIj8PdqSEUMybJYrBa OpjnOssd5RzoNvmkp7QiWTvbTDdzDwc5DRUOFDX9a5Msy/mWzIVTgPxmCpYV57US 9so1uazqSK7JxS/b4RppISv1ry4yWnLp26qOk9iSJCQ/tebk2+0WW1KslJQvO1dM 9W0W2CxtxlZL76whBpQZ+qX8Oa3b1kLUJUp15pphNpaLX4JrZrh7/goYqSUXfsm1 gCt2XcGOSxPNfWbKycdZ64zAKCAnPzf7Gb/rjEmTJGUwy7JasnrFmITG2SXdumXE xFyeKuFS87aVheu4Rvn6815ccM02uCbZpGa9RTnk45jcTGlngaefmpDCBmC6c4NR eRZKFKA0Q4B54Oh4pVNTcToEtpeunyJf7x2Dv+IQywapkK90hGG3I9kKi9riyRTS 4foW4/fcKTP6Ts6fxI9QOCkcv+BG5FRqC8TquEZ5uN+LC64ZyDW3fvd57kbI+rpV mzwZuebQ3eauWKva2Z2nmIbQe7vYh/SeLM0Scfq41MV2WdJnsahtEd6zaExwTfvI 1dHdffB4jAK5kDb5XWbVlcbkC1AJi3I9ECzD4vnPmZ2GYcllYJuexoZKzNhzZWa+ yHEBLkun8J7U8mG/MdTZk+fpuzWKa5RLcfvTL8fokEuQyzekbymt5YjFpKzSikkO CiXsdIn4AipVMUJVe/AG+fYm4ZZenEn5ljUVcv1oLMKNFyeHCUaLkZsWwEaxmgMb GEX1DF2NAQpgnF9kPx7nphe4j5xjhQdu7fVS5RHnVAgN446wvVxehlx6/LVn3QXs C55VmtfB/ntWJqG8T1J/kg+PDxs0fMbGlVE0Xw4covYUjMJxUiS8VvkkJhcpgcAu ABuD2ftOzhwAom+w+Zx1JmZ3ORESvkxpk3D311VwTSAQGIHgmkAgMALBNYFAYASC awKBwAgE1wQCgREIrgkEAiPwP1inMB/IgqkYAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC"> <p style="top:25.6pt;left:289.8pt;line-height:7.0pt">M. Asif et al.: Emotion Recognition Using Temporally Localized Emotional Events</p> <p style="top:205.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt"><b>FIGURE 7.</b> F1 scores of SEED vs DENS for all the 25 trials.</p> <p style="top:229.4pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">Fig. 7 shows an F1 score comparison between SEED</p> <p style="top:241.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">and DENS datasets per trial. Using t-test statistical test-</p> <p style="top:253.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">ing, the 25 F1 score of SEED dataset (M = 95.65%,</p> <p style="top:265.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">SD = 0.37%) compared with the 25 F1 score of DENS dataset</p> <p style="top:277.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">(M = 97.68%, SD = 0.13%), DENS dataset shows better</p> <p style="top:289.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">results with absolute t (31) = 25.466,<i> p</i><i> &lt;</i> 0<i>.</i>0001, Cohen’s</p> <p style="top:301.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">d estimate: −11.37 (large), 95 percent confidence interval:</p> <p style="top:313.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">[−13.73 −9.02].</p> <p style="top:338.7pt;left:37.2pt;line-height:9.0pt"><i>C. COMPARISON WITH OTHER RECENT STUDIES</i></p> <p style="top:350.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">We have included some other recent studies and given a</p> <p style="top:362.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">comparative table for their results in Table 3. The studies</p> <p style="top:374.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">consist of CNN-RNN Hybrid models, R2G-STNN model</p> <p style="top:386.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">that is based on regional to global BiLSTM with Attention</p> <p style="top:398.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">layer, Attention-based CNN-RNN Hybrid model (ACRNN),</p> <p style="top:410.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">BiDCNN that is Bi-hemisphere Discrepancy CNN model and</p> <p style="top:422.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">ECLGCNN that is a fusion model of Graph CNN and LSTM</p> <p style="top:434.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">model.</p> <p style="top:460.2pt;left:37.2pt;line-height:9.0pt"><b>V. DISCUSSION</b></p> <p style="top:471.4pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">In this work, we captured emotional experiences within the</p> <p style="top:483.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">ecologically valid naturalistic environment with a precise</p> <p style="top:495.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">temporal marker than any study to date. As per recent</p> <p style="top:507.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">theories, emotional experience is a constructing phenomenon</p> <p style="top:519.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">which involves networks of the brain, including the default</p> <p style="top:531.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">mode network, salience network, and fronto-parietal net-</p> <p style="top:543.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">work. These networks are not specific to emotional experi-</p> <p style="top:555.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">ences. In fact, these networks are domain-general networks</p> <p style="top:567.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">which are involved in perception (in general). Though,</p> <p style="top:579.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">the connectivity among these networks might not be the</p> <p style="top:590.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">same in different perceptions which is apparently shown in</p> <p style="top:603.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">our previous work [35]. In addition, different from normal</p> <p style="top:615.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">perception, emotional experiences involve changes in body</p> <p style="top:627.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">physiology [29]. Putting together the above-mentioned ideas</p> <p style="top:638.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">from recent results hints that the emotional experiences can</p> <p style="top:650.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">be easily confused with other perceptions, which might not</p> <p style="top:662.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">be an emotional experience.</p> <p style="top:674.8pt;left:46.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">One of the major concerns is the mind-wandering activity</p> <p style="top:686.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">while using the film stimuli. In the previous research, the</p> <p style="top:698.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">whole stimulus is considered to elicit a single emotional</p> <p style="top:710.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">experience. And the duration of the stimulus varied from</p> <p style="top:722.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">seconds to minutes. Research shows that averaging the</p> <p style="top:65.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">participant’s feedback for the whole duration of the stimulus</p> <p style="top:77.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">might not be correctly capturing emotional experience (in</p> <p style="top:89.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">particular) [36]. Hence, it is important to know the duration</p> <p style="top:101.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">of the emotional experience without compromising the</p> <p style="top:113.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">ecological validity of the stimuli.</p> <p style="top:125.0pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">The main idea behind this work is that if we can capture</p> <p style="top:137.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">the temporal marker of emotional experience within a</p> <p style="top:148.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">real-life resembling environment, we might achieve better</p> <p style="top:160.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">accuracy than the accuracy achieved to date with other</p> <p style="top:172.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">datasets lacking information about time. Although, due to</p> <p style="top:184.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">the limited number of subjects, we didn’t go for the subject-</p> <p style="top:196.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">independent classification for now. Though, in future, we will</p> <p style="top:208.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">be collecting more data to mitigate this limitation.</p> <p style="top:220.6pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">In our results, we observed that the same hybrid deep</p> <p style="top:232.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">learning model on our dataset not only outperformed other</p> <p style="top:244.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">datasets, including benchmark datasets like DEAP and SEED</p> <p style="top:256.5pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">but also achieved a better result when comparing with other</p> <p style="top:268.5pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">noteworthy relevant studies (see Table 3). Classification</p> <p style="top:280.4pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">of DEAP data into four labels, including HVHA, LVHA,</p> <p style="top:292.4pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">LVLA, and HVLA, resulted in 95.65% mean accuracy.</p> <p style="top:304.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">At the same time, the classification of DENS data into</p> <p style="top:316.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">four labels resulted in 96.82% mean accuracy. Similarly,</p> <p style="top:328.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">the classification of SEED data into three labels resulted</p> <p style="top:340.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">in 95.65% mean accuracy while DENS data resulted in</p> <p style="top:352.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">97.68% mean accuracy. The significance testing showed that</p> <p style="top:364.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">even with multiple iterations, the classification accuracy was</p> <p style="top:376.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">significantly higher for our data.</p> <p style="top:388.0pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">To the date, most of the work on emotion recognition</p> <p style="top:400.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">applied different shallow machine learning and deep learning</p> <p style="top:411.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">techniques using many different configurations of input</p> <p style="top:423.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">data including, spectrogram, raw signals, statistical features,</p> <p style="top:435.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">variational mode decomposition (VMD), empirical mode</p> <p style="top:447.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">decomposition (EMD), functional connectivity based fea-</p> <p style="top:459.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">tures, fractal features and so on. However, still, the recog-</p> <p style="top:471.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">nition of emotion from EEG stands as a problem. Most of</p> <p style="top:483.7pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">the works on emotion recognition have used some benchmark</p> <p style="top:495.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">datasets, including DEAP, SEED, AMIGO, MAHNOB-HCI</p> <p style="top:507.6pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">and so on. Though, most of the emotion classification works</p> <p style="top:519.5pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">revolve around DEAP and SEED datasets [2].</p> <p style="top:531.5pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">In [37], emotional states are classified by means of EEG-</p> <p style="top:543.4pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">based functional connectivity patterns. Forty participants</p> <p style="top:555.4pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">viewed audio-visual film clips to evoke neutral, positive (one</p> <p style="top:567.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">amusing and one surprising) or negative (one fear and one</p> <p style="top:579.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">disgust) emotions. Correlation, coherence, and phase syn-</p> <p style="top:591.3pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">chronization are used for estimating the connectivity indices.</p> <p style="top:603.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">They stated significant differences among emotional states.</p> <p style="top:615.2pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">A maximum classification rate of 82% was reported when</p> <p style="top:627.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">the phase synchronization index was used for connectivity</p> <p style="top:639.1pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">measure.</p> <p style="top:651.0pt;left:307.0pt;line-height:10.0pt">The classes considered in the study are elementary.</p> <p style="top:663.0pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">We suspect that with the increasing number of emotional</p> <p style="top:674.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">classes, which includes not only basic classes but complex</p> <p style="top:686.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">emotions as well, taking the long-duration signal without a</p> <p style="top:698.9pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">temporal marker may not be able to categorize emotional</p> <p style="top:710.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">classes. The reason is that there are fewer chances for a movie</p> <p style="top:722.8pt;left:297.1pt;line-height:10.0pt">stimulus to have a positive as well as a negative emotional</p> <p style="top:745.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">39922</p> <p style="top:746.6pt;left:489.2pt;line-height:6.0pt">VOLUME 11, 2023</p> <img src="/media/images/image_10_1.png" alt="Image 1"><div id="page0" style="width:576.0pt;height:782.9pt"> <p style="top:25.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:7.0pt">M.
