yeViMHDiSx0si7es3dJBsskyJSlr/B2TCAPkt3V9PyLW4xp5qesUq+Ka4rebAX35 aCgLp4xRYMp7JfcePhumg8U9XLtPVbE3gmwD7Guuq8pfe76VL6S2jsLZja59Y+2V axRNjs419us5gGvWbo55MHxKl2Tnm/VYWz7LidK6sf1i4Q+6u0jMx/S91yycrC0v CK7ZN9cUp3rI6TPuX1Jk6TAzdcl3PVkVmBPb11f+2ct3rCwl2X+jTfisMN0XeSKd FTHK2juQ3FlJzPzH2vn6E7VfOhmuGdATbx6IlZI6jOQa/XZIj8PdqSEUMybJYrBa OpjnOssd5RzoNvmkp7QiWTvbTDdzDwc5DRUOFDX9a5Msy/mWzIVTgPxmCpYV57US 9so1uazqSK7JxS/b4RppISv1ry4yWnLp26qOk9iSJCQ/tebk2+0WW1KslJQvO1dM 9W0W2CxtxlZL76whBpQZ+qX8Oa3b1kLUJUp15pphNpaLX4JrZrh7/goYqSUXfsm1 gCt2XcGOSxPNfWbKycdZ64zAKCAnPzf7Gb/rjEmTJGUwy7JasnrFmITG2SXdumXE xFyeKuFS87aVheu4Rvn6815ccM02uCbZpGa9RTnk45jcTGlngaefmpDCBmC6c4NR eRZKFKA0Q4B54Oh4pVNTcToEtpeunyJf7x2Dv+IQywapkK90hGG3I9kKi9riyRTS 4foW4/fcKTP6Ts6fxI9QOCkcv+BG5FRqC8TquEZ5uN+LC64ZyDW3fvd57kbI+rpV mzwZuebQ3eauWKva2Z2nmIbQe7vYh/SeLM0Scfq41MV2WdJnsahtEd6zaExwTfvI 1dHdffB4jAK5kDb5XWbVlcbkC1AJi3I9ECzD4vnPmZ2GYcllYJuexoZKzNhzZWa+ yHEBLkun8J7U8mG/MdTZk+fpuzWKa5RLcfvTL8fokEuQyzekbymt5YjFpKzSikkO CiXsdIn4AipVMUJVe/AG+fYm4ZZenEn5ljUVcv1oLMKNFyeHCUaLkZsWwEaxmgMb GEX1DF2NAQpgnF9kPx7nphe4j5xjhQdu7fVS5RHnVAgN446wvVxehlx6/LVn3QXs C55VmtfB/ntWJqG8T1J/kg+PDxs0fMbGlVE0Xw4covYUjMJxUiS8VvkkJhcpgcAu ABuD2ftOzhwAom+w+Zx1JmZ3ORESvkxpk3D311VwTSAQGIHgmkAgMALBNYFAYASC awKBwAgE1wQCgREIrgkEAiPwP1inMB/IgqkYAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC"> <p style="top:25.6pt;left:289.8pt;line-height:7.0pt">M. Asif et al.: Emotion Recognition Using Temporally Localized Emotional Events</p> <p style="top:65.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">experience in the same stimuli, but it is certainly possible that</p> <p style="top:77.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">it can have more than one positive or more than one negative</p> <p style="top:89.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">feeling in the movie.</p> <p style="top:114.2pt;left:37.2pt;line-height:9.0pt"><b>VI. CONCLUSION</b></p> <p style="top:125.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">The work presented in this article is based on the concept</p> <p style="top:137.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">that emotion is a short-lived phenomenon which might last</p> <p style="top:149.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">for very few seconds. Hence, using long-duration EEG</p> <p style="top:161.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">signals recorded during emotional stimulus watching might</p> <p style="top:173.2pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">not contain emotional information for the whole duration.</p> <p style="top:185.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">Therefore, we hypothesized that using only the duration of</p> <p style="top:197.1pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">the signal where an emotional event is reported without</p> <p style="top:209.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">compromising the ecological validity of the stimuli will</p> <p style="top:221.0pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">contain more emotional information. To test the hypothesis,</p> <p style="top:232.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">we designed an EEG experiment which uniquely marks the</p> <p style="top:244.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">duration of the emotional event in the continuous recording of</p> <p style="top:256.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">brain waves using EEG. We performed deep learning analysis</p> <p style="top:268.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">using a hybrid CNN and LSTM model and found results that</p> <p style="top:280.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">significantly favoured our hypothesis. In this work, we saw</p> <p style="top:292.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">the problem with a different aspect which has not attracted</p> <p style="top:304.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">the attention of the researcher. We suggest that future research</p> <p style="top:316.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">on emotion recognition should adapt our approach to collect</p> <p style="top:328.6pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">more such kinds of data so that emotion recognition using</p> <p style="top:340.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">EEG can go beyond the emotions only and move towards</p> <p style="top:352.5pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">recognizing and analyzing more complex emotions.</p> <p style="top:377.7pt;left:37.2pt;line-height:9.0pt"><b>ACKNOWLEDGMENT</b></p> <p style="top:388.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt"># Dataset on Emotion with Naturalistic Stimuli. Availability</p> <p style="top:400.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt">at (https://openneuro.org/datasets/ds003751).<i> (Mohammad</i></p> <p style="top:412.8pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:10.0pt"><i>Asif and Sudhakar Mishra contributed equally to this work.)</i></p> <p style="top:438.0pt;left:37.2pt;line-height:9.0pt"><b>REFERENCES</b></p> <p style="top:451.2pt;left:40.0pt;line-height:7.6pt">[1] I. <p style="top:404.7pt;left:261.9pt;line-height:8.0pt">from</p> <p style="top:414.2pt;left:118.3pt;line-height:8.0pt">the Indian Institute of Information Technol-</p> <p style="top:423.8pt;left:118.3pt;line-height:8.0pt">ogy Allahabad, Prayagraj, India, where he is</p> <p style="top:433.4pt;left:118.3pt;line-height:8.0pt">currently pursuing the Graduate degree. He is</p> <p style="top:442.9pt;left:118.3pt;line-height:8.0pt">also doing research on spatio-temporal dynamics</p> <p style="top:452.5pt;left:118.3pt;line-height:8.0pt">of emotions. He has conducted two important</p> <p style="top:462.0pt;left:118.3pt;line-height:8.0pt">experiments on Indian samples, which results in</p> <p style="top:471.6pt;left:118.3pt;line-height:8.0pt">the availability of stimuli dataset (validated on an</p> <p style="top:481.2pt;left:118.3pt;line-height:8.0pt">Indian sample) and the availability of EEG dataset</p> <p style="top:490.7pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:8.0pt">with unique information about the time of emotional experience during</p> <p style="top:500.3pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:8.0pt">watching the naturalistic multimedia stimuli. He is a member of the Society</p> <p style="top:509.9pt;left:36.2pt;line-height:8.0pt">for Neuroscience.</p> <img
